	<div id="p111265" class="post row-fluid odd">
	
		<div class="postbody span9">
			

			<div class="author">by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6816&amp;sid=a8a07dc8ca935fab95dcf953e3afa0ec">grumpyoldgit</a></strong> &raquo; Thu Jun 28, 2012 9:02 pm </div>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>samwilson001 wrote:</cite>It shows the lo and eth0, lo is configured fine.<br /><br />eth0 has not details filled in as you would expect for a device which can't contact a dhcp server.</div></blockquote><br /><br />Have you allocated any fixed addresses on your network?<br />If, say, you have a device with a fixed address of 192.168.1.10<br />but as far as DHCP is concerned that is the next free address, you will not get a connection.<br /><br />Also, on my router I tried to give my Pi a fixed address using the mac address. The Pi did not like it at all and refused to connect.<br />This last issue seemed to revolve around the Pi giving out new mac addresses, which really confused the router.</div>

			

		</div>

		
